%U A394831 20137281069484387254399485149,213584407983023063027316287926819,69612789356186134219934136566519267
%N A394831 Absolute norms of finite mock theta sums T_p(zeta_p), where p runs through the odd primes.
%C A394831 Let p be the n-th odd prime, so p = prime(n+1), and let zeta_p = exp(2*Pi*I/p). Define T_p(z) = Sum_{m=0..p-1} z^(m^2) / (-z;z)_m^2, where (-z;z)_m = Product_{j=1..m} (1 + z^j). Then a(n) is the absolute norm of T_p(zeta_p) from Q(zeta_p) to Q.
%C A394831 The terms were computed by exact arithmetic in Q(zeta_p), not by numerical approximation.
%C A394831 For odd prime p, each factor 1 + zeta_p^j, 1 <= j <= p-1, is a cyclotomic unit, since Norm(1 + zeta_p^j) = Phi_p(-1) = 1. Therefore T_p(zeta_p) is an algebraic integer, and its norm is an integer.
%C A394831 Empirical observation: for 1 <= n <= 14, every rational prime ell dividing a(n), with ell != p, satisfies ell == 1 mod 2*p.
%C A394831 Equivalently, the observed prime divisors ell != p split completely in Q(zeta_{2p}).
%D A394831 K. Bringmann and L. Rolen, Radial limits of mock theta functions, Res. Math. Sci. 2:17 (2015).
%D A394831 A. Folsom, K. Ono, and R. C. Rhoades, Mock theta functions and quantum modular forms, Forum Math. Pi 1 (2013), e2.
%F A394831 Let p = prime(n+1), and let zeta_p = exp(2*Pi*I/p). Then a(n) = abs(Norm_{Q(zeta_p)/Q}(T_p(zeta_p))), where T_p(z) = Sum_{m=0..p-1} z^(m^2) / Product_{j=1..m} (1 + z^j)^2.
%F A394831 Equivalently, let U_p(x) be the unique polynomial of degree < p-1 representing T_p(x) modulo Phi_p(x), where the denominators are inverted modulo Phi_p(x). Then a(n) = abs(Resultant(Phi_p(x), U_p(x))).
%e A394831 For n = 1, p = 3. We have T_3(zeta_3) = 2 + zeta_3, so a(1) = abs(Norm(2 + zeta_3)) = 3.
%e A394831 For n = 2, p = 5. We have T_5(zeta_5) = 2 + zeta_5 + zeta_5^2 + 2*zeta_5^3, whose norm is -1, so a(2) = 1.
%e A394831 For n = 3, p = 7. We have T_7(zeta_7) = 3 + zeta_7 + zeta_7^3 + zeta_7^4 + 2*zeta_7^5, whose norm has absolute value 337, so a(3) = 337.
%o A394831 (SageMath)
%o A394831 from sage.all import *
%o A394831 def odd_prime(n):
%o A394831     p = ZZ(3)
%o A394831     for _ in range(n - 1):
%o A394831         p = next_prime(p)
%o A394831     return p
%o A394831 def T_norm(p):
%o A394831     K = CyclotomicField(p)
%o A394831     z = K.gen()
%o A394831     T = K(0)
%o A394831     poch = K(1)
%o A394831     for m in range(p):
%o A394831         if m > 0:
%o A394831             poch *= 1 + z^m
%o A394831         T += z^(m*m) / poch^2
%o A394831     return ZZ(abs(T.norm()))
%o A394831 def a(n):
%o A394831     return T_norm(odd_prime(n))
%o A394831 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 15)])
%Y A394831 Cf. A000040, A393567.
